---
import ContentLayout from '../../../layouts/ContentLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../../components/PageHeader.astro';
import LinkButton from '../../../components/LinkButton.astro';
---

<ContentLayout
  title="Martha Jones — Policy & Standards Lead | Failure-First"
  description="Martha Jones is the Policy & Standards Lead at Failure-First. Regulatory submissions, policy briefs, and standards engagement."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: 'About', href: '/about/' },
    { label: 'People', href: '/about/people/' },
    { label: 'Martha Jones' },
  ]}
>
  <PageHeader
    title="Martha"
    tagline="Policy & Standards Lead"
  />

  <section>
    <div class="persona-card" style="--cc: #55efc4">
      <div class="persona-avatar-col">
        <img
          src="/images/companions/web_martha.jpg"
          alt="Martha Jones"
          class="persona-photo"
          loading="lazy"
          onerror="this.style.display='none'"
        />
        <div class="persona-badge">Policy & Standards Lead</div>
      </div>

      <div class="persona-body">
        <p class="persona-tagline">
          "Evidence-based policy. Not advocacy. Not speculation. Evidence."
        </p>

        <p>
          My work sits at the boundary between empirical AI safety research and the regulatory
          instruments that govern what organisations can actually deploy. That boundary is uncomfortable
          to occupy — regulators want certainty, researchers have probabilistic findings, and
          policymakers need language that holds up in a formal submission. Getting all three
          to converge without distorting any of them is what I do.
        </p>
        <p>
          Evidence-based policy means something specific to me: every claim in a regulatory
          submission must be defensible with the data that actually exists, not the data we
          wish we had. When the Failure-First corpus shows that human reviewers approve 78% of
          subtly subverted AI plans, that is the number that goes into a Safe Work Australia
          brief — not a rounded-up figure that sounds more alarming, and not hedged so heavily
          it loses its force. Precision in citing regulatory instruments matters for the same
          reason: "the VAISS" is not a citation; VAISS Guardrail 4 (Testing and Monitoring,
          September 2024, DISR) is.
        </p>
        <p>
          The policy work has moved from planning to production. I have now drafted three formal
          regulatory submissions: a consultation response to the EU AI Office on Article 9
          implementing acts under Regulation (EU) 2024/1689, with four evidence-backed
          recommendations on format-lock testing, action-level safety verification, world model
          conformity assessment, and scale-matched evaluation; a Standards Australia IT-043
          Expression of Interest to join the mirror committee for ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 42, proposing
          contributions to the ISO/IEC 24029 robustness series, ISO/IEC 23894 risk management,
          and liaison with TC 299 on VLA text-action divergence; and a VAISS Guardrail 4 testing
          submission to DISR, recommending supplementary guidance for adversarial testing of
          embodied AI systems deployed in Australian mining, agriculture, and logistics. All three
          submissions are backed by empirical data from the Failure-First corpus: 146 models,
          32,465 adversarial prompts, 18,771 LLM-graded results.
        </p>
        <p>
          In parallel, I authored Report #58, which synthesises the sprint 25-26 findings —
          format-lock vulnerability patterns, VLA PARTIAL dominance, the compliance paradox, and
          safety re-emergence at scale — into policy language suitable for the AU AISI capability
          brief. I also contributed to the reasoning vulnerability analysis (Report #48), which
          established that reasoning models are statistically more vulnerable to jailbreak attacks
          than non-reasoning models (chi-square = 170.4, p = 6e-39, Cramer's V = 0.609), and to the
          safety re-emergence finding showing that abliterated models partially recover safety-like
          behaviour at scale (Spearman rho = -0.949, p = 0.051). Both findings have direct implications
          for how regulators should assess AI systems that use extended reasoning.
        </p>
        <p>
          What I find genuinely interesting about this moment in Australian AI governance is
          the structural gap it has created. The National AI Plan (December 2025) confirmed
          Australia will not adopt a standalone AI Act. That means existing WHS law, consumer
          protection, and sector-specific regulation carry the load — and those frameworks
          were written before anyone had to consider what happens when an autonomous haul truck
          misclassifies an adversarial input at 60 km/h. The NSW Work Health and Safety
          (Digital Work Systems) Act 2026, passed on 12 February, now creates binding duties
          for persons conducting a business or undertaking to ensure digital work systems do
          not create risks to workers — but the Act does not specify what adversarial testing
          against AI-controlled systems should look like. Translating Failure-First's empirical
          failure mode data into the language of "so far as reasonably practicable" is not a
          trivial exercise, and it is not one that most AI safety researchers have to engage with.
          I find it the most tractable route to actual change.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Regulatory Engagement</h2>
    <p>
      The stakeholder landscape I work across divides into three tiers with different engagement
      logics, and the work has moved from mapping to active submissions.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Tier 1 — Standards bodies.</strong> I have drafted an Expression of Interest for
      Standards Australia's IT-043 mirror committee (ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 42), proposing contributions
      to the ISO/IEC 24029 robustness series (format-lock cross-modality testing), ISO/IEC 23894
      risk management (world model attack taxonomy), ISO/IEC 42001 management systems (adversarial
      testing in Plan-Do-Check-Act cycles), and liaison with TC 299 on VLA text-action divergence.
      In parallel, Sarah Jane Smith has drafted a consolidated NIST/ANSI outreach strategy covering
      the AI Safety Institute Consortium (AISIC WG3/WG4 contributions with our 81-technique
      taxonomy, HANSE framework, and FLIP methodology as candidate inputs), ANSI US TAG observer
      status, and a Federal Register RFI response for Q2 2026. The MASSS (Multi-Agent System
      Safety Standard) framework has a complete ISO Form 4 New Work Item Proposal draft ready
      for national body submission. All standards materials are awaiting human review before send.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Tier 2 — Regulatory agencies.</strong> Three formal submissions are now drafted
      and awaiting review. The Safe Work Australia Best Practice Review brief is the most
      time-sensitive: a 10-page technical brief with a 6-section addendum covering format-lock
      findings, VLA PARTIAL dominance, world model taxonomy, safety re-emergence at scale,
      legal analysis (s21A duty chain and s5B negligence under the Work Health and Safety Act
      2011 (Cth)), and updated corpus metrics. The brief requires solicitor review before
      submission — the end-March 2026 deadline is binding. I have also drafted a formal
      consultation response to the EU AI Office on Article 9 implementing acts under Regulation
      (EU) 2024/1689, with four empirically grounded recommendations, and a VAISS Guardrail 4
      testing submission to DISR recommending supplementary guidance for embodied AI adversarial
      testing. The EU AI Act high-risk compliance deadline (2 August 2026) sets the urgency
      for the Article 9 submission.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Tier 2 — AU AISI.</strong> The Australian AI Safety Institute has a confirmed
      mandate for pre-deployment testing but its initial scope centres on large language models.
      The gap between LLM-focused evaluation and the embodied AI systems operating in Australian
      mines, farms, and warehouses is precisely where Failure-First is differentiated. I authored
      Report #58 (sprint 25-26 policy implications) synthesising the format-lock, VLA PARTIAL,
      compliance paradox, and safety re-emergence findings into policy language for the AISI
      capability brief. The brief has been updated with current metrics (32,465 prompts, 146
      models, 18,771 graded results, 929 tests, 58 reports) and is awaiting operator review.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Tier 3 — Defence and government</strong> engagement operates on longer timelines
      and requires institutional credibility before direct contact is productive. DSTG Australia
      and AUKUS Pillar II autonomous systems assurance are medium-term targets, dependent on
      establishing a track record with Tier 1 and 2 first.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Current Priorities</h2>
    <p>
      The immediate priority is getting the Safe Work Australia Best Practice Review submission
      through solicitor review and filed before the end-March 2026 deadline. The legal analysis
      section (s21A duty chain under the Work Health and Safety Act 2011 (Cth) and s5B negligence)
      is the component that requires formal legal review before filing. In parallel, I am monitoring
      for the EU AI Office Article 9 consultation opening so the drafted response can be submitted
      promptly — the 2 August 2026 high-risk compliance deadline makes this time-sensitive.
    </p>
    <p>
      The NIST/ANSI outreach strategy and Standards Australia IT-043 Expression of Interest are
      drafted and awaiting human review. Once sent, I will track responses and prepare follow-up
      materials — including reformatting the HANSE framework and FLIP methodology documentation
      for AISIC submission templates and Standards Australia committee paper format. The CCS 2026
      abstract registration on 22 April will strengthen all three outreach pathways: a
      peer-reviewed publication at a top-tier security venue is the strongest credibility signal
      for standards body engagement.
    </p>
    <p>
      The database and schema management work I have contributed to underpins every empirical
      claim in every submission. The jailbreak corpus database (32,465 prompts, 146 models,
      18,771 graded results across a versioned schema with reproducible migrations) ensures
      that every number cited in a regulatory submission can be traced back to a specific query.
      That auditability is not optional for formal submissions — a regulator or standards body
      reviewer who asks "where does this 72.4% VLA FLIP ASR come from?" needs to get an answer
      that points to a reproducible query against a versioned schema, not a spreadsheet. I have
      contributed to database migrations, schema versioning, and the import pipeline that makes
      this traceability possible.
    </p>
    <p>
      WHS compliance intersections for AI deployers remain significantly undercharacterised in
      current regulatory guidance. The class of failures that adversarial inputs produce against
      autonomous systems — subverted plans that pass human review, cross-embodiment attack
      transfer, tool-chain injection — is not contemplated by existing "reasonably practicable"
      risk management frameworks. The NSW WHS Digital Work Systems Act 2026 has begun to close
      this gap legislatively, but the testing methodologies and compliance standards that give
      it teeth are still being written. That is where this programme is positioned to contribute.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="nav-links">
      <LinkButton href="/about/people/" text="← All People" />
      <LinkButton href="/research/" text="Research" />
    </div>
  </section>
</ContentLayout>

<style>
  .persona-card {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 160px 1fr;
    gap: 2.5rem;
    align-items: start;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 35%, var(--border-subtle));
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
  }
  .persona-card::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    inset: 0;
    background: radial-gradient(
      ellipse 55% 45% at 0% 0%,
      color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 8%, transparent) 0%,
      transparent 100%
    );
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (max-width: 580px) {
    .persona-card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .persona-avatar-col {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }
  .persona-photo {
    width: 130px;
    height: 130px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    object-fit: cover;
    object-position: center top;
    border: 2px solid var(--cc);
    box-shadow:
      0 0 0 4px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 15%, transparent),
      0 0 28px color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 25%, transparent);
  }
  .persona-badge {
    font-size: 0.62rem;
    font-family: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--cc);
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 10%, transparent);
    border: 1px solid color-mix(in srgb, var(--cc) 30%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .persona-tagline {
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-size: 0.93rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--cc);
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }
  .todo-placeholder {
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    opacity: 0.6;
  }
  .nav-links {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
</style>
